PRACTICAL NUMBER 1
NETWORKING DEVICES 
1. Router
â€¢	Function: Connects different networks together; routes data from one network to another.
â€¢	Key Use: Connects home/office networks to the internet.
â€¢	Smart Feature: Assigns IP addresses, provides firewall and security.
2. Switch
â€¢	Function: Connects multiple devices (computers, printers, etc.) within a LAN.
â€¢	Key Use: Forwards data to the specific device it's meant for using MAC addresses.
â€¢	Smarter than: A hub (because it sends data only to the intended device).
3. Hub (Legacy device, less used now)
â€¢	Function: Connects multiple Ethernet devices.
â€¢	Key Use: Broadcasts incoming data to all ports (not efficient).
â€¢	Less intelligent: Doesnâ€™t filter data or know destination devices
 4. Modem (Modulator-Demodulator)
â€¢	Function: Converts digital data from a computer to analog for transmission (and vice versa).
â€¢	Key Use: Connects your home network to your ISP (Internet Service Provider).
â€¢	Types: DSL, Cable, Fiber modems
5. Access Point (AP)
â€¢	Function: Extends a wired network by adding Wi-Fi capability.
â€¢	Key Use: Used in wireless LANs (WLANs).
â€¢	Often built-in: Many routers include built-in access points.

6. Network Interface Card (NIC)
â€¢	Function: Allows a computer to connect to a network.
â€¢	Key Use: Every device on a network needs one.
â€¢	Types: Wired (Ethernet NIC), Wireless (Wi-Fi NIC)

7. Bridge
â€¢	Function: Connects two LANs using the same protocol.
â€¢	Key Use: Divides network into segments to reduce traffic.
â€¢	Smarter than hub: Filters traffic based on MAC addressesðŸ”¹ 8. Gateway
â€¢	Function: Acts as a translator between different network protocols.
â€¢	Key Use: Connects different systems (e.g., enterprise network to the internet).
9. Repeater
â€¢	Function: Boosts or regenerates signals in a network.
â€¢	Key Use: Extends the range of a network by amplifying the signal.
â€¢	Common in: Large buildings or areas with weak signals.
10. Firewall (Hardware or Software)
â€¢	Function: Controls incoming and outgoing network traffic based on security rules.
â€¢	Key Use: Protects against unauthorized access.
11. Brouter (Bridge + Router)
       A Brouter is a hybrid networking device that combines the functions of both a bridge and a router.
TOPOLOGIES
1. Bus Topology
â€¢	Structure: All devices are connected to a single central cable (the bus).
â€¢	Data Flow: Data travels in both directions along the cable.
â€¢	Advantages:
o	Easy and inexpensive to implement.
o	Requires less cable than star topology.
â€¢	Disadvantages:
o	If the main cable fails, the entire network goes down.
o	Difficult to troubleshoot.
o	Limited cable length and number of nodes.

 2. Star Topology
â€¢	Structure: All devices are connected to a central device (hub/switch).
â€¢	Data Flow: Devices communicate through the central device.
â€¢	Advantages:
o	Easy to install and manage.
o	Failure of one node doesnâ€™t affect the rest.
â€¢	Disadvantages:
o	Central device is a single point of failure.
o	Uses more cable than bus topology. 

3. Ring Topology
â€¢	Structure: Each device is connected to two others, forming a circular path.
â€¢	Data Flow: Data travels in one direction (or both in a dual ring).
â€¢	Advantages:
o	Data flows in an orderly manner.
â€¢	Disadvantages:
o	A failure in any cable/device breaks the loop.
o	Troubleshooting is hard.
o	Adding/removing devices disrupts the network.  

4. Mesh Topology
â€¢	Structure: Every device is connected to every other device.
â€¢	Types:
o	Full Mesh: All nodes are interconnected.
o	Partial Mesh: Some nodes are interconnected.
â€¢	Advantages:
o	Very reliable and redundant.
o	Failure of one link doesnâ€™t affect communication.
â€¢	Disadvantages:
o	Expensive and complex.
o	Requires lots of cabling and ports.

 5. Tree Topology (Hierarchical)
â€¢	Structure: A combination of star topologies connected to a central bus or main cable.
â€¢	Advantages:
o	Scalable and structured.
o	Easy to expand.
â€¢	Disadvantages:
o	Failure in the backbone affects the entire network.
o	More cabling.

 6. Hybrid Topology
â€¢	Structure: Combination of two or more different topologies.
â€¢	Example: Star-Bus, Star-Ring.
â€¢	Advantages:
o	Flexible and scalable.
â€¢	Disadvantages:
o	Complex design and maintenance.
o	Costly.

BASIC NETWORK TROUBLESHOOTING COMMANDS
1. ping
â€¢	Purpose: Tests connectivity to another device or website.
â€¢	Usage:
â€¢	ping google.com
â€¢	ping 192.168.1.1
â€¢	What it shows: Whether the target is reachable, response time, and packet loss.
________________________________________
2. ipconfig (Windows only)
â€¢	Purpose: Displays IP address, subnet mask, default gateway, and more.
â€¢	Usage:
â€¢	ipconfig
â€¢	ipconfig /all
â€¢	ipconfig /release
â€¢	ipconfig /renew
â€¢	ipconfig /flushdns
â€¢	Key Uses:
o	/release and /renew help refresh IP address.
o	/flushdns clears the DNS cache.
3. ifconfig (Linux/macOS; deprecated in Linux but still used)
â€¢	Purpose: Shows and configures network interfaces.
â€¢	Usage:
â€¢	ifconfig
Use ip a instead on modern Linux systems.
4. tracert (Windows) / traceroute (Linux/macOS)
â€¢	Purpose: Shows the path (hops) data takes to reach a destination.
â€¢	Usage:
â€¢	tracert google.com      # Windows
â€¢	traceroute google.com   # Linux/macOS
5. nslookup
â€¢	Purpose: Queries DNS to find the IP address of a domain name.
â€¢	Usage:
â€¢	nslookup google.com

6. route
â€¢	Purpose: Displays and manipulates the routing table.
â€¢	Usage:
â€¢	route print       # Windows
â€¢	route -n          # Linux












